\"fn\">M</span> <span class=\"fn\">N</span></span> <a href=\"./Mathlib/Algebra/Module/LinearMap/Defs.html#LinearMap\">→ₛₗ[</a><span class=\"fn\">σ₁₃</span><a href=\"./Mathlib/Algebra/Module/LinearMap/Defs.html#LinearMap\">]</a> <span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/TensorProduct/Defs.html#TensorProduct\">TensorProduct</a> <span class=\"fn\">R₂</span> <span class=\"fn\">M₂</span> <span class=\"fn\">N₂</span></span> <a href=\"./Mathlib/Algebra/Module/LinearMap/Defs.html#LinearMap\">→ₛₗ[</a><span class=\"fn\">σ₂₃</span><a href=\"./Mathlib/Algebra/Module/LinearMap/Defs.html#LinearMap\">]</a> <span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/TensorProduct/Defs.html#TensorProduct\">TensorProduct</a> <span class=\"fn\">R₃</span> <span class=\"fn\">M₃</span> <span class=\"fn\">N₃</span></span></div></div>","info":{"doc":"This is a binary version of `TensorProduct.map`: Given a bilinear map `f : M ⟶ P ⟶ Q` and a\nbilinear map `g : N ⟶ S ⟶ T`, if we think `f` and `g` as semilinear maps with two inputs, then\n`map₂ f g` is a bilinear map taking two inputs `M ⊗ N → P ⊗ S → Q ⊗ S` defined by\n`map₂ f g (m ⊗ n) (p ⊗ s) = f m p ⊗ g n s`.\n\nMathematically, `TensorProduct.map₂` is defined as the composition\n`M ⊗ N -map→ Hom(P, Q) ⊗ Hom(S, T) -homTensorHomMap→ Hom(P ⊗ S, Q ⊗ T)`.\n","docLink":"./Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/TensorProduct/Map.html#TensorProduct.map₂","kind":"def","line":199,"name":"TensorProduct.map₂","sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/8f9d9cff6bd728b17a24e163c9402775d9e6a365/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/TensorProduct/Map.lean#L199-L210"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/TensorProduct/Map.html#TensorProduct.homTensorHomMap\"><span class=\"name\">TensorProduct</span>.<span class=\"name\">homTensorHomMap</span></a></span><span class=\"impl_arg\"><span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">{<span class=\"